<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-04-09T00:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-04-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="911" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d911">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102S/2457: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-04-09T12:00:00+07:00">April 9,
                                    1941—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 3:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Your [<hi rend="italic">Shanghai’s</hi>] April 8, 4 p.m. I have today
                            written informally to the Foreign Minister pointing out the situation
                            described in your reference telegram and expressing the hope that the
                            Chinese Government will take steps to see that this threat to the peace
                            and order of the International Settlement is removed.</p>
                        <p>Sent to Shanghai, repeated to Department, Peiping.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>